docs.abstract: A newly created post will oversee intelligence collection and analysis on foreign influence campaigns and efforts to attack election infrastructure.
docs.snippet: A newly created post will oversee intelligence collection and analysis on foreign influence campaigns and efforts to attack election infrastructure.
docs.lead_paragraph: ASPEN, Colo. — An experienced official will oversee election security intelligence across the government in a newly created senior position, the director of national intelligence announced on Friday as part of an effort to improve coordination and speed response to attacks by foreign governments.

headline.main: Intelligence Chief Names New Election Security Oversight Official
headline.print_headline: New Post Will Keep Eye Out for Foreign Meddling in U.S. Elections

docs.abstract: A three-judge panel said a lower court judge hearing a lawsuit by congressional Democrats had not adequately considered questions about separation of powers.
docs.snippet: A three-judge panel said a lower court judge hearing a lawsuit by congressional Democrats had not adequately considered questions about separation of powers.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A federal appeals court delivered a setback on Friday to a lawsuit by congressional Democrats accusing President Trump of illegally benefiting from his business interests while in office, saying a lower court judge hearing the suit had not adequately considered questions about the separation of powers between the president and Congress.

headline.main: Appeals Court Judges Send Emoluments Suit Against Trump Back to a Lower Court

docs.abstract: A raft of election-security legislation faces opposition from the Senate majority leader, but House Democrats are readying hearings and votes to raise the pressure.
docs.snippet: A raft of election-security legislation faces opposition from the Senate majority leader, but House Democrats are readying hearings and votes to raise the pressure.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A raft of legislation intended to better secure United States election systems after what the special counsel, Robert S. Mueller III, called a “sweeping and systematic” Russian attack in 2016 is running into a one-man roadblock in the form of the Senate majority leader, Mitch McConnell of Kentucky.

headline.main: New Election Security Bills Face a One-Man Roadblock: Mitch McConnell
headline.print_headline: Election Security Bills Hit One-Man Snag: McConnell

docs.abstract: “Right now China is getting absolutely decimated” over American tariffs, the president asserted.

docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump on Monday defended his administration’s decision to threaten a number of trading partners like Mexico with tariffs, calling tariffs a “beautiful thing” and asserting that a trade deal with China was close because of his aggressive policies.

headline.main: Trump Defends ‘Beautiful’ Tariffs as a Negotiating Tactic

docs.abstract: Staff Sgt. Kevin Maxwell Jr. told a military court that he and three other American commandos engaged in hazing during which the soldier was strangled.
docs.snippet: Staff Sgt. Kevin Maxwell Jr. told a military court that he and three other American commandos engaged in hazing during which the soldier was strangled.
docs.lead_paragraph: NORFOLK, Va. — A Marine commando pleaded guilty on Thursday to negligent homicide charges in the 2017 death of a Green Beret soldier in Mali, describing how he helped duct-tape the wrists and feet of the victim, who was choked in a hazing incident.

headline.main: Marine Pleads Guilty to Hazing Death of Green Beret in Mali

docs.abstract: The mayor’s office confirmed that the president intends to speak from the Lincoln Memorial, prompting criticism that he is politicizing a nonpartisan celebration.
docs.snippet: The mayor’s office confirmed that the president intends to speak from the Lincoln Memorial, prompting criticism that he is politicizing a nonpartisan celebration.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Since early in his tenure, President Trump has sought to stage a military parade through the heart of Washington, only to be thwarted. So now he has settled on the next best thing: He will take over an existing patriotic display in the capital.

headline.main: Trump Sets Off Fireworks of a Different Sort With Fourth of July Speech Plan
headline.print_headline: Fears of ‘the Angriest July 4 Ever’ as Trump Seizes Top Billing on the Mall

docs.abstract: At a news conference in London, the president says Republican senators would be “foolish” to try to stop him.
docs.snippet: At a news conference in London, the president says Republican senators would be “foolish” to try to stop him.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — President Trump on Tuesday said he plans to move forward with imposing tariffs on Mexican imports next week as part of his effort to stem the flow of migrants crossing the southern border, telling reporters at a news conference with British Prime Minister Theresa May that Republican senators would be “foolish” if they try to stop him.

headline.main: Mexico Will Face Tariffs Next Week, Trump Vows

byline.original: By Maggie Haberman and Nicholas Fandos

docs.abstract: A bipartisan group of senators will try to force votes rebuking the White House’s decision to circumvent Congress to sell munitions to Saudi Arabia.
docs.snippet: A bipartisan group of senators will try to force votes rebuking the White House’s decision to circumvent Congress to sell munitions to Saudi Arabia.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A bipartisan group of senators will try to force nearly two dozen votes rebuking the Trump administration’s decision to declare a national emergency to circumvent Congress and sell billions of dollars of munitions to Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates.

headline.main: Senators Look to Force 22 Votes Blocking Arms Sales to Saudi Arabia
headline.print_headline: Senators’ Protest of Mideast Arms Deals Will Ring Out in 22 Votes

docs.abstract: The disconnect between President Trump and his third national security adviser has sown confusion around the world about America’s foreign policy.
docs.snippet: The disconnect between President Trump and his third national security adviser has sown confusion around the world about America’s foreign policy.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump was grousing about John R. Bolton, his national security adviser, at his Florida club not long ago. Guests heard the president complaining about the advice he was getting and wondering if Mr. Bolton was taking him down a path he did not want to go.

headline.main: Trump Undercuts Bolton on North Korea and Iran
headline.print_headline: Trump Diverges From Key Adviser On Iran and Kim

byline.original: By Peter Baker and Maggie Haberman
